{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3565529,"name":"Bill Kinahan","username":"kinahawi","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/k/d2c977/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-22T20:35:37.083Z","cooked":"<p>We’re using a command which creates and schedules a sequential command group.<br>
In our command, our isFinished function simply returns the value of the isFinished function of the newly created sequential command group (SCG). We’re finding that the value returned from the SCG never returns true. Digging deeper, we found that the SCG does indeed end and that the isFinished function momentarily returns true (when the command index is equal to the last command in the list), but the end() function overwrites the index to -1 so subsequent calls to isFinished return false. Is this desired behavior? Should isFinished also look for -1? Alternately, is there a point in the SCG class setting the index to -1 if it will never be called again by the scheduler?</p>
<p>Perhaps what we’re doing is not advisable so I’m interested in alternatives to our approach.</p>
